snippet.title: Toy Song | A Simple Song for Kids Learning English | ESL
snippet.description:
You can learn more about this toy song as well as find free printable flashcards, worksheets and games based on the song on my blog at http://www.englishforkidz.com/2016/12/toys-song-for-children.html 

Toys are the things that surround kids from the very first days of their lives. So children would surely love to watch this video and listen to my toy song that I sang with my little son. The song is simple enough to be used by English teachers and moms to teach the language to kids and especially to those who learn English as foreign language. It sounds as simple as a nursery rhyme. Ans it's just what is needed to teach and entertain all the young children from babies and toddlers to early school kids.

snippet.title: Learn Colors with Dump Trucks Part 2 | Educational Video for Kids by Brain Candy TV
snippet.description:
Become a valued member of our Brainiac Club on Patreon at https://www.patreon.com/braincandytv and receive fun perks like voting on upcoming topics, getting your name in the credits and more, all while helping to support our show. Thanks for helping us continue to create quality educational videos for kids around the world!

Your kids will love learning their colors with this fun educational video featuring colorful dump trucks transporting loads of toys from the toy factory to the toy stores across town.  We'll identify the colors of the toys and also find the mixed up toy with the wrong color.

In this video, we'll learn about the colours pink, white, gray, black, cyan (or teal or turquoise) and brown.  We'll also review all of the colours we learned in part one: red, orange, yellow, green, blue and purple.

I hope this fun visual presentation helps your little ones to learn their colors and how to apply them to everyday objects.

Fruits are the means by which angiosperms disseminate seeds. Edible fruits, in particular, have propagated with the movements of humans and animals in a symbiotic relationship as a means for seed dispersal and nutrition; in fact, humans and many animals have become dependent on fruits as a source of food. Accordingly, fruits account for a substantial fraction of the world's agricultural output, and some (such as the apple and the pomegranate) have acquired extensive cultural and symbolic meanings.

In botany, a fruit is a seed-bearing structure in flowering plants (also known as angiosperms) formed from the ovary after flowering.

In common language usage, "fruit" normally means the fleshy seed-associated structures of a plant that are sweet or sour, and edible in the raw state, such as apples, bananas, grapes, lemons, oranges, and strawberries. On the other hand, in botanical usage, "fruit" includes many structures that are not commonly called "fruits", such as bean pods, corn kernels, tomatoes, and wheat grains. The section of a fungus that produces spores is also called a fruiting body.

snippet.description:
This telling time video helps kids learn how to tell time quickly and accurately with both digital and traditional (analog) clocks. Please subscribe to Rock 'N Learn's YouTube channel for more fun videos posted every week.

Click a time below to jump to any part of this video:

06:43   Telling Time to the Half Hour

Telling time is a breeze with the help of Timothy Time, the Clock that Rocks, and his comical friends. Fun music, catchy rhymes, and colorful animation entertain kids of all ages. 

Timothy Time is more than a lovable character. He knows how to clearly explain the concepts of telling time. Unfortunately, many kids do not know how to tell time using an analog clock – one with hands. This the perfect solution.

This video starts off easy and gives clear examples along with lots of humor and musical entertainment. Kids learn to tell time to the half hour, quarter hour, five minutes, and eventually to the minute. This video provides plenty of review and practice so that students build their skills every time it is used.
